title: Excitation functions of (a,xn) reactions on Rb-natural and Sr-natural from threshold up to 26 MeV: possibility of production of Y-87, Y-88 and Zr-89

x4freetext: Excitation functions of (a,xn) reactions on Rb-natural
and Sr-natural from threshold up to 26 MeV: possibility
of production of Y-87, Y-88 and Zr-89

x4codes.shortRef: Jour: Applied Radiation and Isotopes, Vol.65, p.561 (2007)

x4freetext: Nat-Rb(Cl), 99.99% and nat-SrCO(3), 99.99% were used.
Thin samples of strontium carbonate were prepared. A
thin Al-foil, 25-mu-m thick and 13-mm in diameter, was
used as backing. A suspension of very fine strontium
carbonate in ethanol was obtained by mixing and
stirring. To avoid contamination, the surface of the
sample was covered with a 10-mu-m thick Al-foil.
For preparing samples of rubidium chloride, the powder
was pressed on a Al-foil of 10 mu-m thickness and 13-mm
diameter under a pressure of 6 ton/cm**2 for 10-15-min.
Samples of thickness 18-22-mg/cm**2 were obtained. They
were mechanically stable. Also in this case each sample
was covered with a 10 mum thick Al-foil.
.With available in the literature data.
Integral yields of the products were calculated-

The total uncertainty in the measured cross
section was obtained by taking the square root of the
sum of the squares of all the estimated individual
uncertainties and was 15%.
The error in average target thickness is
less than 1%.
The error in target non-homogeneity is 4%.
The error in the detector
efficiency is 5-10%.
The error in counting statistics and peak
area analysis is less than 4%.
The error in beam current is 8-10%.
The uncertainty in the alpha-particle energy
effective at a sample ranged between 0.8 and 1.8-MeV
for Rb(Cl) samples, the highest uncertainty being
associated with the samples at the end of the stack.
For SrCO(3) samples, it was only between 0.4 and

the data of Levkovskij (Inter-Vesti, Moscow,1991) in

present data and Levkovskij`s data. See A0510
